  "notes": [
    "UC Santa Cruz students may choose to complete one or more minors, provided they can finish all required coursework within their maximum enrollment terms and allowable credits. While a minor will appear on a student's official transcript, it will not be listed on their diploma. Pursuing a minor is a personal decision that should align with a student's educational and career goals. Students do not apply for minors when submitting their application to UC Santa Cruz. After enrolling, transfer students interested in pursuing a minor should contact the department offering the minor for guidance.",
    "Prospective transfer students interested in minoring in chemistry are encouraged to complete the following courses, or their articulated equivalents, prior to transferring: General Chemistry series (see group 1 below) See \"General Chemistry Series\" below for important information Organic Chemistry series (see group 2 below) Calculus series (see group 3 below) One of the following options: (see group 4 below) MATH 22 – Introduction to Calculus of Several Variables MATH 23A – Vector Calculus AND MATH 23B – Vector Calculus AM 30 – Multivariate Calculus for Engineers ﻿ Introductory Physics series (see group 5 below) Refer to the “Preparation for the Minor” section below for courses approved to apply to each of the requirements listed above. It is strongly recommended that community college students complete all General Chemistry coursework for their intended major at one institution prior to transfer to UC Santa Cruz. Additionally, not all community colleges offer a full year of Organic Chemistry that matches UCSC's Organic Chemistry sequence. As a result, students may need to take some Organic Chemistry courses at UC Santa Cruz, even if they’ve completed a full year of introductory Organic Chemistry at a community college. Please visit the Chemistry & Biochemistry website to learn more about this minor.",
    "Prior to July 1, 2023, UC Santa Cruz's General Chemistry series was offered as Chemistry 1A, 1B and 1C, with associated laboratories Chemistry 1M and 1N. Starting in the 2023-2024 academic year, this series was replaced by two new distinct series: Chemistry 3A, 3B and 3C, with labs Chemistry 3BL and 3CL; and Chemistry 4A and 4B with labs Chemistry 4AL and 4BL. Prospective transfer students who started working toward the Chemistry 1 series prior to the 2024-2025 academic year may complete equivalent courses as originally approved, and their articulated coursework will fulfill the General Chemistry series requirement for this minor."
